-- FTSE 100 Benchmark Retreats As Fed Weighs Stimulus; Cobham Shares Slide
-- B y   A d a m   H a i g h
-- 2010-11-03T16:45:58Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-02/888-holdings-plc-bae-systems-firstgroup-rbs-u-k-irish-equity-preview.html
U.K. stocks declined as investors
waited to hear if the Federal Reserve has plans to pump more
money into the U.S. economy.  Cobham Plc  sank 9.5 percent after saying underlying profit
growth could be limited this year.  Next Plc  fell 2.2 percent
after the U.K.’s second-biggest clothing retailer forecast a
“tougher” end to the year.  Admiral Group Plc  climbed 2.6
percent after the U.K. car insurer that owns the Confused.com
website said it’s “on track” to meet analysts’ consensus
profit estimates for 2010.  The benchmark  FTSE 100 Index  lost 8.46, or 0.2 percent, to
5,748.97 at the 4:30 p.m. close in London. The measure rallied
2.3 percent last month amid speculation the Federal Reserve’s
Open Market Committee will unveil another round of bond
purchases to boost growth at its meeting that concludes today.
The FTSE All-Share Index declined 0.2 percent and Ireland’s  ISEQ
Index  climbed 0.7 percent today as  CRH Plc  rallied.  “In the near term, we remain cautious as to the market
reaction to the FOMC press release,”  Christian Parisot , a
Paris-based strategist at Aurel BGC, wrote in an e-mail to
clients today. “Stock markets could ‘sell the news.’ Investors
have focused on these liquidity injections but they could react
very negatively to a limited programme amount, given the Fed’s
very gloomy economic analysis.”  The Fed today may pledge to purchase $500 billion or more
in securities, 29 of 56 economists in a Bloomberg survey said.  Cobham  Cobham slumped 9.5 percent to 211.5 pence. Profit growth
could be limited this year, held back by delays and deferrals in
defense and security contracts in the U.S., the company said in
a statement today.  Next  fell 2.2 percent to 2,180 pence after the retailer
said a sales decline worsened in the third quarter.  Admiral rose 2.6 percent to 1,670 pence. Sales in the three
months to Sept. 30 rose to 446 million pounds ($715 million)
compared with 294 million pounds in the year-earlier period, the
Cardiff, Wales-based insurer said in a statement today. The
company said it is “on track” to meet analysts’ consensus
profit estimates for 2010.  Lloyds Banking Group Plc  gained 2.7 percent to 69.2 pence
as Britain’s biggest mortgage lender named Antonio Horta-Osorio,
head of Banco Santander SA’s U.K. unit, as chief executive
officer, replacing Eric Daniels.  Building materials maker CRH rallied 3.2 percent to 13.05
euros in Dublin.  To contact the reporter on this story:
 Adam Haigh  in London at 
